05248nam a22009135i 9780674063136DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2012    mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740631367 a10.4159/harvard.97806740631362doi  a(DE-B1597)178120  a(OCoLC)777191942  a(OCoLC)840440544  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aPQ4496.E23bS58 2012eb 7aPOE0050302bisacsh04a851/.12221 aPetrarch, Francesco, eauthor.10aSonnets and Shorter Poems /cFrancesco Petrarch, Francesco Petrarca, David R Slavitt. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00t Frontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tTRANSLATOR'S PREFACE -- tSONNETS AND SHORTER POEMS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this volume, David R. Slavitt, the distinguished translator and author of more than one hundred works of fiction, poetry, and drama, turns his skills to Il Canzoniere (Songbook) by Petrarch, the most influential poet in the history of the sonnet. In Petrarch's hands, lyric verse was transformed from an expression of courtly devotion into a way of conversing with one's own heart and mind. Slavitt renders the sonnets in Il Canzoniere, along with the shorter madrigals and ballate, in a sparkling and engaging idiom and in rhythm and rhyme that do justice to Petrarch's achievement.At the center of Il Canzoniere (also known as Rime Sparse, or Scattered Rhymes) is Petrarch's obsessive love for Laura, a woman Petrarch asserts he first saw at Easter Mass on April 6, 1327, in the church of Sainte-Claire d'Avignon when he was twenty-two. Though Laura was already married, the sight of her woke in the poet a passion that would last beyond her premature death on April 6, 1348, exactly twenty-one years after he first encountered her. Unlike Dante's Beatrice-a savior leading the poet by the hand toward divine love-Petrarch's Laura elicits more earthbound and erotic feelings. David Slavitt's deft new translation captures the nuanced tone of Petrarch's poems-their joy and despair, and eventually their grief over Laura's death. Readers of poetry and especially those with an interest in the sonnet and its history will welcome this volume.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 7aPOETRY / European / General.2bisacsh1 aPetrarca, Francesco, eauthor.1 aSlavitt, David R, eauthor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2012z9783110288995oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE ENGLISH LINGUISTICS AND LITERATURE 2012z978311028890208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET LINGUISTIK UND LITERATURWISSENSCHAFT  2012z9783110288896oZDB-23-DGA08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP Complete eBook Package 2011-2014z978311037488908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package 2012z978311037491908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045951708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066256640uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.9780674063136423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674063136.jpg  a978-3-11-028890-2  E-BOOK PACKAGE ENGLISH LINGUISTICS AND LITERATURE 2012b2012  a978-3-11-037488-9  HUP Complete eBook Package 2011-2014  a978-3-11-037491-9  HUP eBook Package 2012b2012  a978-3-11-044220-5  HUP eBook Package Backlist 2005-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-045951-7  HUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-066256-6  HUP eBook Package Backlist